status_message:
Update (2/14, 2:48 p.m.) All 12 members of the basketball team as well as 3 coaches have been examined by hospital personnel. None of their injuries were life-threatening and all have been released to their families.

= 

Update (2/13, 8 p.m.) All 12 members of the basketball team as well as 3 coaches have been examined by hospital personnel. None of their injuries were life-threatening and most have already been released to their families and are on their way home. One student awaits further testing.

==

The Penn State Lehigh Valley men's basketball team has been involved in a major accident today (Feb. 13) at around 10 a.m. on their way to a game in New Kensington, Pa. It has been reported that the charter bus on which they were traveling was hit by a tractor trailer on I-78 near Fryestown, Pa. Police are on the scene. At this time there are no reports of serious injury to anyone on the bus and all are being transported to a local hospital for medical attention as a precautionary measure.
 
There were several other vehicles also involved in accident. Emergency services are on site.  We will continue to update this information as more facts are known.
link_name: Penn State Lehigh Valley men's basketball team involved in bus accident | Penn State University

#TBT -- In March 1944, college and universities across the United States began preparing for a flood of admissions applications from servicemen returning from the Second World War. Penn State (and other institutions across the country) planned to erect temporary dormitories to house this avalanche of incoming students.
Here's a late 1940s aerial view of Penn State's Windcrest Village and Pollock Circle, housing for student veterans returning from WWII. The complexes were located about where South Halls is today on the University Park campus. Tune in tonight to WPSU's "Higher Education in Focus" for more about Penn State's resources for veterans.
Image: University Archives
link_name: Post-WWII and eager for a Penn State education | Penn State University

status_message:
Over the last several days, dozens of "White Student Union" pages sprouted on Facebook claiming to be affiliated with various universities, including Penn State.

The University was alerted over the weekend of this page using Penn State's name and athletic logo. We were in the process of requesting that Facebook take the page down, when it was removed from the site. This page had no affiliation with our University and we found it disturbing and uncivil. We will be watching closely to ensure that the page does not resurface in another form.

status_message: #TBT celebrates the early shift from analog to digital at Penn State. Harold I. Tarpley, a faculty member teaching about power generation and transmission, led Penn State into the computer age. Proclaimed Tarplev, "A few years ago the electronic computer was pretty much a laboratory 'child.' With great suddenness this child has become a giant." In 1956, he and Arthur Waynick, head of the electrical engineering department, set out to build their own "giant" that, according to a 1957 account in the Daily Collegian student newspaper, could "perform 1,400 additions of 10-digit numbers in one second, and its magnetic drum can store 2.5 thousand 10-digit figures." status_message:
A new universal hotline, combining the Ethics and Compliance, Report Bias and Sexual Assault and Relationship Violence, is available for reporting concerns about all misconduct. The phone number for the combined Penn State Hotline is 800-560-1637. Reports can also be made online at http://hotline.psu.edu. 

The hotline, active since Aug. 24, was one of the recommendations made by the Task Force on Sexual Assault and Sexual Harassment.

An independent third party administers the hotline 24 hours a day, seven days a week, and reports can be made anonymously and without fear of retaliation. For calls regarding sexual assault or relationship violence, callers will be connected with confidential support services at their geographic location.

Throwback Thursday -- With Tussey Mountain in the distance, then-Pennsylvania State College Dean of Agriculture Ralph Watts stands on a barn roof and preaches the gospel of scientific agriculture to a gathering of farmers in the early 1900s. Penn State's mission from the beginning included spreading the word about the latest developments in modern agriculture to farming communities across Pennsylvania. Numerous "field days" were organized statewide, precursors of today's Ag Progress Days -- a three-day event held each August at the Russell E. Larson Agricultural Research Center at Rock Springs, that attracts more than 400 exhibitors and 45,000 visitors. Image: University Archives

"We have a wide variety of attractions designed to appeal to virtually everyone, from commercial exhibits and field demonstrations highlighting the latest agricultural technology, to gardening advice, food demonstrations, horse exhibitions and kids' activities." College of Agricultural Sciences, Penn State University Ag Progress Days is Aug. 18-20.

Flashback Friday: Snoopy the Snowman at the steps of Old Main on  Jan. 16, 1975.

While we don't know who the young woman is in the photo, after featuring it in Thursday's Penn State Today, we heard from 1976 mechanical engineering grad Todd Figard, who built the snowman with Ray Trunzo: 

"Ray 'Hoagie' Trunzo (BS '76/MS Aerospace Eng) and I built Snoopy on the railing the evening prior to this photo while on the way back to Hamilton Hall from an excursion downtown. It was a wet snow perfect for snowman building and one thing led to another and Snoopy was the end result of about 3 hours effort. To keep him from falling over, we used a broken safety barrier to form his spine with the V-shaped legs supporting his upper arms. His ears wear a pair of old socks with his eyes a split squashball. We found an old shirt for the scarf and used a twig to help keep it extended like he was actually flying. His nose would up being dyed with black ink because all of my racketballs were blue or green.

"I have since lost track of Ray since he migrated from LA to New Jersey I think, but maybe he or someone who knows him will see this and pass it along."

Flashback Friday: The Lion in winter is a timeless image. This photograph was taken nearly 50 years ago and though Penn State and the statue's immediate surroundings have changed significantly since 1966, the statue itself is the same (save a crack on the right ear). Originally a gift from the Class of 1940, it was carved on-site by noted sculptor Heinz Warneke, from a single 13-ton block of Indiana limestone. The Lion Shrine was dedicated in 1942.

Flashback Friday: This week we look to the history of a Commonwealth Campus -- Penn State Berks, pictured here in the 1960s when it was the Berks Center.

The Wyomissing Polytechnic Institute, housed in an old church, closed in 1958 and gave its building to Penn State for an extension center. By 1972 it moved to its current 106-acre site in Spring Township and became the Penn State Berks campus. Today, it enrolls more than 2,800 students and offers 19 baccalaureate degrees. Read more about its history: http://bit.ly/1Djicr8

Flashback Friday: Before there was The Nittany Lion, there was Old Coaly, pictured here with original owner Piersol Lytle in the late 1850s. Though never officially adopted as a Penn State symbol, Coaly was held in high esteem. Brought to campus from Kentucky by Lytle in 1857, Coaly helped in construction of Old Main, hauling limestone blocks.  He had an extraordinary capacity for work, and for 30 years handled many landscaping and farm chores around campus. 

Coaly was so beloved that after his death in 1893, his skeleton was preserved as a relic of Penn State's past. It's now on display in the HUB-Robeson Center. (Photo: University Archives)

status_message:
We find Penn Staters everywhere! Yesterday we met Robert Kannapel, Class of 1966, at a Cape Cod League baseball game in Yarmouth, Mass. 

His first career out of college was as a Marine Corps officer. He told us that after 13 months in Vietnam, on what was supposed to be his last day in country, he ran over a landmine in an amphibious tank, injuring his arm. He remembers fondly being among the first classes to attend a game at Beaver Stadium, which he noted at the time only had a capacity of just more than 45,000. 

Tell us, have you met a Penn Stater in an unexpected place this summer?
Surprises at every turn: Summer's full blooms, Childhood's Gate Children's Garden, HUB construction area's unusual visitor and a stylized view of Beaver Stadium. Enjoy the tour!

Flashback Friday: This familiar location at the corner of College Ave. and Allen St. has had many occupants since it was first built in 1855, the same year Penn State was founded. The corner's initial establishment was Jack's Road House, the first rooming house in the area to offer food and lodging for travellers. This circa 1895 photo shows when the Nittany Inn was on the corner. In 1926 it was renamed the Hotel State College. (Photo: University Archives)

Flashback Friday: Students spend some free time at the Creamery, then located in Borland Lab, in 1956. 

Originally in the old College Barns and then a one-story standalone building, from 1904 to 1932 the Creamery was located in Patterson Building. After 74 years in Borland and outgrowing the facility, Penn State Berkey Creamery opened in the new Food Science Building, with a store two and a half times the size of the old one. Flashback Friday: Ever wonder what this tiny brick building (seen here in 1939) behind Armsby Building is? Inside is the Penn State Armsby Calorimeter, built in 1902 to perform experiments on the energy metabolism of cattle. Later on it was converted for studying metabolism in sheep, and eventually also humans. In 1969 the small building was converted into a museum. (Photo: University Archives)

Flashback Friday: Stone House circa 1891. Also known as Elm Cottage, it was built in 1880 as a residence for Penn State's vice president. In 1928 it became home to the University's first women's social club, Nita-Nee, founded in 1921. Nita-Nee became Kappa Alpha Theta in 1930, making Stone House the first sorority residence. It was used for other purposes after 1949 and was razed in 1971. A stone tablet on the HUB lawn marks the former site of the house.

Flashback Friday: In 1905, Calvin Waller became the first black student  to graduate from Penn State. Originally from Georgia and majoring in agriculture, "Cal" was associate editor of La Vie, a member of Alpha Zeta agricultural fraternity and the natural history club, and quarterback for the intramural football team. He was also an accomplished vocalist and president of the Glee Club. 

After graduation, he became head of the agricultural department at Prairie View A&M University in Texas, and also headed agricultural extension for black farmers for the entire state. More on Cal Waller: http://goo.gl/GbDGho

Flashback Friday: 140 years ago this month the Agricultural College of Pennsylvania became the Pennsylvania State College. James Calder, the college's 5th president, felt that it was time to abandon the concept of being primarily an agricultural institution and initiated sweeping changes, including broadening the curriculum and gradually phasing out the system of manual labor, which was never popular with the students.

In 1953, the Pennsylvania State College would become the Pennsylvania State University.

Flashback Friday: It's Dec. 21, 1938. About 150 Penn State students are boarding this special train at the Bellefonte Central Railroad station along Atherton Street to take them home for their holiday break. The station, at far right, is now the State College bus station and the tracks have long been removed. Once a favored mode of travel by students, special trains at holiday and semester break gave way to cars and buses. The 1938 train was the last of its kind.

On this day 72 years ago, the USS Pennsylvania was docked at Pearl Harbor and was one of the first ships to return fire following the surprise attack. The U.S. Navy builder's model of the Pennsylvania, depicting the ship as it appeared when commissioned by the Navy in 1916, is housed on the third floor of Wagner Building at University Park.

The ship's bell resides outside Wagner, and two of its gun barrels are located at the Pennsylvania Military Museum in nearby Boalsburg. For more photos and history: http://goo.gl/nyCsyr

Flashback Friday: The interior of an East Halls room at University Park in 1962. When completed, East Halls was considered the largest of its kind at any U.S. college campus. The 15-unit complex was built on farm land which was then considered quite far from the center of campus, a fact testified to by its residents -- mostly freshmen -- who would walk to and from class across the infamous Parking Lot 80, an especially memorable trek in winter. (Photo: University Archives)

The due date will differ. The earliest possible due date is Dec. 6. Please check your bill to see when it is due. If needed, you can request a two week extension on eLion. Please remember, a late fee will be charged if payment is received after the bill due date.

This image of "ghosts" walking along Penn State's "Ghost Walk" was taken in the 1890s, a double exposure photograph made by Professor William Buckhout of his daughters and their friends. Professor William Waring planted the two rows of Norway Spruce and Austrian Pine in the 1860s, and 19th century legend claimed that strange apparitions could be seen at night along the path between the trees, which was also popular as a lovers' lane. One Norway Spruce remains standing behind Old Botany.
We are... haunted? How a rich heritage of ghost stories has played a part in passing on Penn State history and traditions. Happy Halloween, Penn Staters!

The oldest continuing student organization on campus, Penn State Thespians was founded in October of 1897. The club was open only to men, apparently because theatrical acting wasn't considered "proper" for ladies; there were few female students anyway. This photo shows three "ladies" -- all played by men -- from the 1901 production of the comic play "David Garrick." World War I caused a shortage of men on campus, and in 1918 women were included for the first time.

Flashback Friday: Boxing -- shown here in Rec Hall circa 1940 -- was among Penn State's most popular intercollegiate sports in the 1920s & '30s, sometimes drawing larger crowds than football. On a Saturday night, wrestling and basketball contests were just "warm ups" early in the evening, and boxing was the main event. In 1932, Penn State won the first official national championship in the sport.

After WWII, boxing's popularity declined sharply and the sport was discontinued in 1954. Today, boxing is a highly competitive club sport at Penn State.

Flashback Friday: Since we've been talking about Rec Hall this week, here's a look at the building from above in the 1940s. The markings on the roof were navigation aids for airplanes and were common at a time when planes had few instruments and pilots relied on visual clues

Opened in 1929, Recreation Building, as it is formally called, was first expanded in 1953 and a major addition came in 2006. Five Penn State teams have won national championships on the Rec Hall floor: boxing (1929 and 1932), wrestling (1953) and men's gymnastics (1960 and 2007). It was once the home to THON and commencement and has played host to numerous concerts and high-profile speakers, including U.S. presidents and presidential candidates and in 1965 Martin Luther King, Jr. (Photo: University Archives)

status_message: Flashback Friday: Atherton Hall, seen here soon after its opening as a women's dormitory in 1938, honors Frances Washburn Atherton, rather than her legendary husband, Penn State's fourth president, George W. Atherton. "Fanny" and George came to Penn State in July 1882. A teacher, Fanny converted part of the president's house into a schoolroom for children of the college faculty. In the mid-1890s she helped found what is today the State College Woman's Club, which advocated successfully for the establishment of a baccalaureate program in home economics in 1906. (Photo: University Archives)

Flashback Friday: This 1940 photo shows a class visiting Henry Varnum Poor as he works on a detail of Abraham Lincoln on the Land-Grant Frescoes in Old Main. Lincoln signed the Morrill Land-Grant Act in 1862, which mandated the study of agriculture, engineering and military science -- a bold departure from the existing collegiate curriculum -- to higher education institutions in return for federal support. Penn State gained its land-grant status in 1863. The frescoes, initiated by a gift from the class of 1932, are currently undergoing conservation.

Flashback Friday: In this World War II-era photo, students in the Army Corps of Cadets march near Schwab Auditorium.

America's entry into World War II brought substantial changes to Penn State, which geared up to support the national defense effort. Undergraduate enrollment plummeted as many male students enlisted or were drafted. Others finished their studies as part of the military reserve before going off to war, receiving special defense-related training in addition. Despite the sharp decline in undergrads, the campus was crowded with military and civilian personnel enrolled in special training classes in such diverse defense-related fields as diesel engineering, map-reading, aeronautics and mechanical drawing. (Photo: University Archives)

Flashback Friday: Although The Nittany Lion was "born" in 1904, many years passed before he appeared at athletic events, and even then was as an African lion. This is the very first photo known to have been taken of the Nittany Lion at a football game-- Penn State vs. Syracuse at New York's Polo Grounds on Oct. 28, 1922.

The "man in the suit" that day was Richard Hoffman '23, who was chosen at least partly because he played a lion in a Penn State Players' production of Androcles and the Lion. Hoffman, who later became a physician, recalled "it was hotter than the Mojave inside that lion suit." Not until the class of 1940 presented the gift of the Nittany Lion shrine in 1942 was the lion firmly established as a mountain lion. (Photo: University Archives)

Flashback Friday! This train was a rolling lab for students in Penn State's railway mechanical engineering program. This photo was taken from College Avenue around 1912. Engineering Unit E, the building with the skylights in the roof, can be seen in the background.

Professor A. J. Wood (standing fifth from right atop the tender in long gray coat) began the railway engineering program in the early 1900s. It was discontinued in the 1930s. Wood and his students operated the train between State College and Bellefonte over the Bellefonte Central Railroad. 

The Pennsylvania Railroad donated both the locomotive and, behind it, the dynamometer car, which measured various aspects of the locomotive's performance.  (Photo: University Archives)

Flashback Friday!

Beginning in 1914, the May Pole dance became a Penn State tradition.

At that time, male students outnumbered females by 2,251 to 80 -- and those 80 were determined to be the fairest of them all.

May Day was a medieval festival that observed the coming of spring with merrymaking. The first May Queen was Mildred Ride Dunlap ('14). She and her Grecian-clad nymphs danced and intertwined long satin ribbons around a May Pole. The Cadet Band played, the public was invited, and proceeds went to the College Hospital Fund.

Over the years, the festival became more elaborate. Our photo shows the way participants looked in 1925.

After World War II, the celebration seemed frivolous and expensive, and the event ended in 1959.

(University Archives photo)

As a Penn State student, in 1875 Bellefonte, Pa., native John Montgomery "Monte" Ward led other students in organizing the University's first intercollegiate baseball squad. (Ward  didn't stay long enough to earn his degree, but he graduated from Columbia with a law degree in 1885.)

Ward went on to become a man of many firsts:
-- first Penn Stater to become nationally known as an athlete, pitching for the New York Giants, among other major league teams
-- first pitcher to perfect the curve ball; in fact, he threw such a pitch often as a student player, as Penn State Professor William Buckhout confirmed through empirical observation
-- formed the first labor union in professional sports, in response to the infamous "reserve clause" that gave team owners virtually all control over players. 

In 1964 Ward became the first ‚Äì and only (so far) -- Penn Stater to be inducted into the Baseball Hall of Fame.

status_message:
Flashback Friday!

Penn State's first president, Evan Pugh, was a newlywed of only a few months when he died on this week in April 1864. 

He and Rebecca Valentine, the daughter of a prominent Bellefonte family, were married that February. Pugh, already weakened from a carriage accident the previous year and physically and mentally overworked, succumbed to typhoid twelve weeks later. 

Although she had other suitors, notably James A. Beaver, who later played an influential role in Penn State's history, Rebecca never remarried and resided in Bellefonte until her death in 1921. Evan and Rebecca are buried in Bellefonte's Union Cemetery.

(University Archives photos)

Flashback Friday!

April is National Poetry Month. 

Renowned poet Theodore Roethke began teaching at Penn State in 1936. In 1941, he published his first book, "Open House." He donated the manuscript and galley proof of that collection to the library.

In 1939, Roethke became Penn State's varsity tennis coach. He's shown here with one of his teams. (Roethke is at left in the second row.)

Roethke's squads compiled an overall record of 29 wins to 21 losses from 1939 to 1943.

Roethke left Penn State for a position at the University of Washington in the mid 1940s. In 1954, he won the Pulitzer prize for poetry.

Read more: http://goo.gl/4qV5P

(University Archives photo)

The Centre Furnace Mansion (left) in the snow in 1904 and (right) just a few days ago, 109 years later.

It looks much as it may have when Moses Thompson and his family moved here in 1842, adjacent to his Centre Furnace iron works. Thompson and his wife, Mary Irvin Thompson, resided at the mansion for 49 years and hosted many social and business gatherings for Penn State trustees, administrators, faculty and guests.

Thompson and James Irvin -- Thompson's business partner, fellow ironmaster, and brother-in-law -- were instrumental in selecting the site of the campus for Penn State, soon after the new college's chartering in 1855, and Irvin made the initial donation of 200 acres of land. 

The mansion, located at the corner of Porter Road and College Avenue, is now home to the Centre County Historical Society.

(University Archives photo; Penn State photo)

status_message:
Flashback Friday!

This 1910 bird's-eye perspective of what was then the Pennsylvania State College is one of a series of college campus views done by Richard Rummell. 

College Avenue, seen in the lower left foreground, is dominated by the Main Engineering Building (destroyed in a 1918 fire) at the foot of Allen Street. 

Rummell's hand-drawn and watercolored original painting is on display in the University Archives in Paterno Library. A tinted version can be purchased in local print and frame shops. 

Fewer than a dozen of the buildings shown are still standing today.

(University Archives photo)

In 2013 Penn State celebrates the 150th anniversary of the conferral of its first graduate degree. 

On Jan. 6, 1863, C. Alfred Smith became the first student at any American college or university to receive the degree of Master of Scientific Agriculture.

Smith had already made history as a member of Penn State's first baccalaureate class in 1861. He joined the faculty as a professor of chemistry and physics and later served as an alumni representative on the Board of Trustees.

Since then, the University has awarded more than 100,000 advanced degrees. Today it offers more than 150 graduate-degree programs, typically conferring about 3,000 master's and doctoral degrees each year.

Forty years ago today, Charles Millard (pictured) and his wife Irma founded the Four Diamonds Fund on the same day their son Christopher lost his battle with pediatric cancer. The Four Diamonds -- courage, wisdom, honesty and strength -- are symbolic of the traits Christopher believed necessary to battle the disease. The student-run Penn State Dance Marathon annually benefits the Four Diamonds Fund, which supports children with cancer, their families and research, at Penn State Milton S. Hershey Medical Center. It has raised $89 million to date. For more about Chris Millard's story: http://goo.gl/v4wfa

status_message:
Candles, flowers and notes have been placed on the Old Main patio in honor of the victims of the tragedy in Newtown, Connecticut.

The center note says, "This light burns for the victims, families, and friends of the tragedy in Newtown, CT. If you pass by and it has gone out, please relight it."

The smaller note quotes Dickens: " 'Charity, mercy, forbearance and benevolence were all my business.' And so they will always be our business."

We are devastated by the tragedy in Connecticut today. The hearts of the Penn State family are with the victims, their families and the entire Newtown community. Words alone cannot express our sorrow, nor can they begin to describe the anguish the families and the community must feel. May they find peace and know that our thoughts and prayers are with them.

The Agriculture Experiment Station was the first agriculture building on campus. Built in 1889, the station was founded by President George Atherton as one of America's first centers for agricultural science research. 

In 1975 the building was renamed and today houses studios for art students and faculty. Although altered from the original design several times, it still stands on 'Ag Hill' near Armsby building at University Park.

Flashback Friday!

University Park got snow this week, and we thought you might like to see what the campus used to look like in winter.

This photo taken in 1926 shows the original Old Main. The building had three years to live at that time (it was razed and rebuilt at the end of the decade).

Even when this photo was taken, it was in such decrepit condition that it housed mostly administrative offices. The upper floors were vacant.

The picture was rarely if ever published prior to our colleague Laura Stocker's discovery of it deep in the University Archives.

Local farmers line up to deliver milk to the Penn State Creamery, then located in Patterson Building, in the 1920s.

status_message:
Flashback Friday!

It's the Ghost Walk -- named for a legend about a student who got lost and froze to death during a blizzard in the 1860s.

The path between two rows of Norway spruce and Austrian pine trees ran from behind Old Botany approximately where Burrowes Building now stands.

Horticulture Professor William Waring planted the grove in the 1860s. Because of its seclusion, it became a meeting place for students and a popular lovers' lane.

But those aren't real ghosts in the photo. They're a group of girls including the daughters of Professor William Buckhout, who made the double-exposure photo in the 1890s.

In 1929 many of the trees were removed due to deterioration and only one -- a Norway Spruce -- remains standing today.

Tell us your best Penn State ghost story.

status_message:
Flashback Friday!

In the fall of 1954, Penn State enrolled its first known set of triplets -- the McCloskey sisters, Jean, Joyce, and Julie, natives of Washington D.C. They chose majors in elementary education, art education, and home economics, respectively. 

In announcing this unusual event, the Penn State Alumni Alumni News reported that in addition to pursuing their studies, the three redheads "were available, separately or together, for baby sitting." 

Only Joyce went on to graduate from the University, receiving a B.S. in 1958. All eventually married and had families, and sadly, all are now deceased.

status_message:
It's the Blue Band!

Not quite. This photo probably dates from the late 1890s, when the band uniforms were brown.  

In 1899, steel magnate and Penn State Trustee Andrew Carnegie gave a donation to purchase instruments for a newly formed Cadet Band, which superseded a fife-and-drum corps. This photo shows a fife and drum unit with buglers, perhaps transitioning toward the Cadet Band, which had more brass. 

Within a few years, the Cadet Band was playing at football games, dances in the Armory, and similar campus and community functions and by 1913 was re-named the College Band. In the 1920s, blue uniforms replaced brown, and the name "Blue Band" came into common usage.

status_message:
Flashback Friday!

Welcome to the Devil's Den, one of several temporary wood-frame residence halls hastily built in time to house some of the incoming students in the fall of 1904. It could house about 50 students. It was located about where Electrical Engineering East building stands today. This view looks toward Pollock Road (which runs behind Devil's Den). At far right you can see the newly completed Carnegie Building along with part of another temporary dorm, Bright Angel. No idea how they got their names. They were demolished soon after completion of new permanent student housing, McAllister Hall, in 1905.

(Our thanks to Mike Bezilla for the information.)

status_message:
Flashback Friday!

 It may look like a wreck, but it's not. It's the aftermath of the 1926 Pajama Parade, during which upper classmen would turn out the frosh in the middle of the night and send them to collect all sorts of movable stuff on campus and in the borough. It was then piled in a heap and the owners would have to come and collect their items next day. 

Unsurprisingly, the 1926 Pajama Parade brought an end to the tradition.

Photo courtesy of the University Archives.

status_message:
Keep your skin safe this summer!

Some tips from Penn State Hershey Medical Center:

-- Generously apply a broad-spectrum, water-resistant sunscreen, with SPF of 30 or more, to all exposed skin. Broad-spectrum provides protection from both ultraviolet A (UVA) and ultraviolet B (UVB) rays. Re-apply approximately every two hours, even on cloudy days, and after swimming or sweating.

-- Wear protective clothing such as a long-sleeved shirt, pants, a wide-brimmed hat and sunglasses, when possible.

-- Seek shade when appropriate, keeping in mind that the sun's rays are strongest from 10 a.m. to 4 p.m. A good rule of thumb is that you should seek shade if your shadow is shorter than you.

-- Protect children from sun exposure by encouraging them to play in the shade, and dress them in protective clothing and apply sunscreen often.

-- Use extra caution near water, snow and sand, as they reflect the damaging rays of the sun and can cause sunburn.

-- Get vitamin D safely through a healthy diet that may include vitamin supplements.

-- Avoid tanning beds. Ultraviolet light from the sun and tanning beds can cause skin cancer and wrinkling. As an alternative, use a sunless self-tanning product and continue to use sunscreen with it.

-- Perform regular self-exams. If you notice anything changing, growing or bleeding on your skin, see a dermatologist. Skin cancer is very treatable when detected early enough.
